src/reactive/prometheus_mysql_exporter_h.message:
So the reactive framework (charms.reactive) evaluates whether to run a decorated function on every single hook invocation.  i.e. install, config-changed, upgrade-charm, *-relation-available, *-relation-connected, etc.  All of them.

Thus once the flags on this function (snap.... and prometheus...) are both true, this function will then run for ever subsequent hook.  This doesn't sound like what is needed.  Thus a "gating" or "run once" type flag is needed, such as "local.prometheus.send-connection-info", which you would use like this:


    @reactive.when("...")
    @reactive.when("...")
    @reactive.when_not("local.prometheus.send-connection-info")
    def send_prometheus_connection_info():
        target = reactive.relations.endpoint_from_flag("prometheus.available")
        if target:
            with charm.provide_charm_instance() as instance:
                ...
                # when it's all sent
                reactive.set_flag("local.prometeus.send-connection-info")

The only caveat is that the flag needs to be cleared (in another handler) iff the connection info needs to be sent again.  Thus flags are mapped to small pieces of functionality and then the flags are switched on/off to run those functions as needed.

This is a slightly dangerous pattern which can lead to some non-obvious errors.  If config-changed hook fails for some other reason and this function never gets run, then it will never be run again on any new good as `config.changed.<flag>` won't be set next time.

Personally, as this is a fairly loosely coupled change, I would do:

    @reactive.when('config.changed')
    def set_config_changed_snap_check():
        reactive.set_flag("snap.prometheus_exporter.check-config-changed")

and then:

    @reactive.when("snap.prometheus_exporter.check-config-changed")
    def maybe_update_snap_channel():
        ...
        reactive.clear_flag("snap.prometheus_exporter.check-config-changed')

Although a bit boring in terms of boilerplate, it does ensure that the charm will eventually get around to checking the config, etc. and then clearing the flag.

